1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,340
A wonderful testimony. Betty, thank you for blessing me this morning.

2
00:00:06,060 --> 00:00:08,980
I also want to direct your attention to the baptistry here.

3
00:00:09,060 --> 00:00:12,120
We've got another baptism, second service, some junior high students.

4
00:00:12,760 --> 00:00:17,960
I just want to say that we're going through a lot of water around here, and that's a good thing.

5
00:00:19,050 --> 00:00:23,190
We've got about 25 people in the next 30 days or so that are going to be baptized.

6
00:00:23,610 --> 00:00:26,010
So you just look out for it each and every week, and praise the Lord.

7
00:00:26,550 --> 00:00:29,790
God's doing a great work in our midst, and we're proud to share that with you.

8
00:00:31,790 --> 00:00:33,030
We come to Palm Sunday.

9
00:00:34,140 --> 00:00:36,700
Jesus comes into Jerusalem.

10
00:00:37,380 --> 00:00:39,380
His final hours are approaching.

11
00:00:40,700 --> 00:00:46,240
And the people worship Jesus by laying down the palm fronds at his feet.

12
00:00:48,270 --> 00:00:53,510
What will you lay at Jesus' feet in worship this season?

13
00:00:53,950 --> 00:00:59,620
What will you place at his feet as an act of love and adoration?

14
00:01:00,720 --> 00:01:06,030
As Betty already shared, Jesus wants your whole life, your spiritual gifts.

15
00:01:06,750 --> 00:01:11,230
He wants your talents, your time, your possessions, all of it.

16
00:01:11,790 --> 00:01:16,750
How will you worship Him this day and each and every day?

17
00:01:19,630 --> 00:01:23,170
We are in the midst of a campaign, as you have probably gathered by now,

18
00:01:23,170 --> 00:01:28,530
and I want to say again, if you are a guest with us, this is a family matter.

19
00:01:28,530 --> 00:01:33,710
but I trust that the message we share and the word of God that we open today

20
00:01:33,710 --> 00:01:35,770
will also be a blessing to you.

21
00:01:36,290 --> 00:01:40,310
But we want you to feel under absolutely no obligation or pressure

22
00:01:40,310 --> 00:01:44,370
to give to this campaign unless God is speaking to you.

23
00:01:44,810 --> 00:01:49,010
This is Family Matters, but I do believe that God's word is exciting

24
00:01:49,010 --> 00:01:51,390
and will be a blessing for you today.

25
00:01:52,390 --> 00:01:57,190
I want to recap some themes from last week and bring us up to speed if you missed it.

26
00:01:57,190 --> 00:02:03,810
And I want to share from Ecclesiastes this morning, chapter 5, a different passage.

27
00:02:03,930 --> 00:02:06,850
We didn't look at this last week, but I want to share it this morning.

28
00:02:07,210 --> 00:02:08,850
It's really been a blessing to me.

29
00:02:11,140 --> 00:02:16,120
And he writes this, those who love money will never have enough.

30
00:02:17,170 --> 00:02:20,830
How absurd to think that wealth brings true happiness.

31
00:02:22,140 --> 00:02:26,360
The more you have, the more people come to help you spend it.

32
00:02:26,680 --> 00:02:29,430
So what is the advantage of wealth?

33
00:02:29,650 --> 00:02:33,190
Except, perhaps, to watch it run through your fingers.

34
00:02:34,930 --> 00:02:39,790
People who work hard sleep well, whether they eat little or much,

35
00:02:40,090 --> 00:02:44,790
but the rich are always worrying and seldom get a good night's sleep.

36
00:02:46,120 --> 00:02:48,820
There is another serious problem I have seen in the world.

37
00:02:49,440 --> 00:02:53,360
Riches are sometimes hoarded to the harm of the saver,

38
00:02:53,800 --> 00:02:59,480
or they are put into risky investments that turn sour and everything is lost.

39
00:02:59,480 --> 00:03:04,660
In the end, there is nothing left to pass on to one's children.

40
00:03:05,760 --> 00:03:11,700
People who live only for wealth come to the end of their lives as naked and empty-handed

41
00:03:11,700 --> 00:03:13,920
as on the day they were born.

42
00:03:16,500 --> 00:03:20,720
I'm going to share those passages again with a little paraphrase.

43
00:03:21,680 --> 00:03:25,740
And I think you'll see how this text speaks to us so profoundly today.

44
00:03:26,140 --> 00:03:27,200
Verse 10 says,

45
00:03:27,200 --> 00:03:30,560
Those who love money will never have enough.

46
00:03:30,560 --> 00:03:37,240
how absurd to think that wealth brings true happiness. Here's the paraphrase, the more you

47
00:03:37,240 --> 00:03:46,810
have, the more you want. The more you have, the more you want. In addition, the more you have,

48
00:03:47,270 --> 00:03:56,620
the less you're satisfied. It's the same thing put differently. Verse 11, he says, the more you have,

49
00:03:56,620 --> 00:03:59,460
the more people come to help you spend it.

50
00:04:00,330 --> 00:04:02,030
So what is the advantage of wealth

51
00:04:02,030 --> 00:04:05,610
except perhaps to watch it run through your fingers?

52
00:04:07,170 --> 00:04:08,890
We'll paraphrase, the more you have,

53
00:04:09,030 --> 00:04:11,570
the more people will come after it,

54
00:04:12,300 --> 00:04:13,200
including the government.

55
00:04:14,040 --> 00:04:15,820
Everybody wants to help you

56
00:04:15,820 --> 00:04:17,820
take some of that off your shoulders.

57
00:04:19,100 --> 00:04:21,220
The more you have, the more you realize

58
00:04:21,220 --> 00:04:23,100
it does you no good.

59
00:04:26,580 --> 00:04:30,670
Verse 12, people who work hard sleep well.

60
00:04:30,670 --> 00:04:38,730
Whether they eat little or much, but the rich are always worrying and seldom get a good night's sleep.

61
00:04:40,140 --> 00:04:43,720
Friends, the more you have, the more you have to worry about.

62
00:04:45,240 --> 00:04:48,680
And as I shared last week, millionaires never smile.

63
00:04:50,220 --> 00:04:51,220
They're always worrying.

64
00:04:54,280 --> 00:04:59,610
Verse 13, there is another serious problem I have seen in the world.

65
00:05:00,170 --> 00:05:03,570
Riches are sometimes hoarded to the harm of the saver.

66
00:05:03,570 --> 00:05:10,270
The more you have, the more you can hurt yourself by holding on to it.

67
00:05:11,580 --> 00:05:14,580
It's not good for our souls to hold on to things.

68
00:05:18,120 --> 00:05:18,940
Verse 14,

69
00:05:21,380 --> 00:05:26,860
Or they put into risky investments that turn sour, and everything is lost.

70
00:05:28,290 --> 00:05:31,230
In the end, there's nothing left to pass on to one's children.

71
00:05:32,680 --> 00:05:36,640
Friends, the more you have, the more you have to lose.

72
00:05:39,990 --> 00:05:41,330
And finally, verse 15,

73
00:05:42,640 --> 00:05:48,440
People who live only for wealth come to the end of their lives as naked and empty-handed

74
00:05:48,440 --> 00:05:50,060
as on the day they were born.

75
00:05:51,700 --> 00:05:55,500
The more you have, the more you'll simply leave behind.

76
00:05:58,030 --> 00:06:04,990
What Solomon is trying to teach us, the moral he's trying to give to us, is that affluence

77
00:06:04,990 --> 00:06:06,370
doesn't satisfy.

78
00:06:06,970 --> 00:06:14,140
And as we saw last week, affluenza, if you will, is a disease that can rot your soul

79
00:06:14,140 --> 00:06:15,220
if you're not careful.

80
00:06:16,060 --> 00:06:18,660
The antidote, as we talked about, to affluenza

81
00:06:18,660 --> 00:06:22,560
is to give, is to have a heart that gives.

82
00:06:22,680 --> 00:06:26,720
And when you give, your soul is shaped

83
00:06:26,720 --> 00:06:30,120
more like God, who's a God who gives.

84
00:06:32,680 --> 00:06:35,340
I think we can see the need to give regularly.

85
00:06:35,500 --> 00:06:37,360
I think we understand that,

86
00:06:37,400 --> 00:06:39,580
and after passages like this, we can say,

87
00:06:40,100 --> 00:06:43,860
yes, I understand, but we still struggle with doing it.

88
00:06:43,860 --> 00:06:48,040
we struggle with giving to God as an act of worship

89
00:06:48,040 --> 00:06:51,660
because we think that if we have just a little more,

90
00:06:52,240 --> 00:06:56,800
then we'll be satisfied and then we can afford to give to God.

91
00:06:58,550 --> 00:07:01,830
It's like, if I can just get this much more

92
00:07:01,830 --> 00:07:03,930
and buy that first

93
00:07:03,930 --> 00:07:07,110
and put a little more money into this and that,

94
00:07:07,490 --> 00:07:10,230
then we can start thinking about giving to God.

95
00:07:10,630 --> 00:07:13,630
And from that perspective, friends,

96
00:07:13,710 --> 00:07:15,370
we're always giving from our affluence,

97
00:07:15,370 --> 00:07:25,640
from our overflow instead of from our obedience and trust in God and His provision in our lives.

98
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:33,860
You see, God calls us to give as an act of worship, to give our best, to give Him the first

99
00:07:33,860 --> 00:07:39,280
fruits of what we've received. God knows that when we give those first fruits that we're putting Him

100
00:07:39,280 --> 00:07:47,510
first in our lives. That's why He asks us to do it that way. And then we have to trust God to take

101
00:07:47,510 --> 00:07:56,780
care of the rest. Listen to what Jesus says in Matthew chapter 6. Don't store up treasures

102
00:07:56,780 --> 00:08:04,750
here on earth where they can be eaten by moths and get rusty and where thieves break in and steal.

103
00:08:06,220 --> 00:08:12,980
Store your treasures in heaven where they will never become moth-eaten or rusty and where they

104
00:08:12,980 --> 00:08:21,280
be safe from thieves. Wherever your treasure is, there your heart and thoughts will also be.

105
00:08:22,740 --> 00:08:30,700
No one can serve two masters, for you will hate one and love the other, or be devoted to one and

106
00:08:30,700 --> 00:08:40,110
despise the other. You cannot serve both God and money. So I tell you, don't worry about everyday

107
00:08:40,110 --> 00:08:46,870
life. Whether you have enough food, drink, and clothes, doesn't life consist of more than food

108
00:08:46,870 --> 00:08:53,950
and clothing? Look at the birds. They don't need to plant or harvest or put food in barns because

109
00:08:53,950 --> 00:09:03,390
your heavenly Father feeds them, and you are far more valuable to Him than they are. Can all your

110
00:09:03,390 --> 00:09:11,480
worries add a single moment to your life? Of course not. And why worry about your clothes?

111
00:09:11,920 --> 00:09:18,320
Look at the lilies of the field and how they grow. They don't work or make their clothing,

112
00:09:18,820 --> 00:09:26,110
yet Solomon in all his glory was not dressed as beautifully as they are. And if God cares

113
00:09:26,110 --> 00:09:33,360
so wonderfully for flowers that are here today and gone tomorrow, won't he surely care for you?

114
00:09:33,360 --> 00:09:36,740
You have so little faith.

115
00:09:38,320 --> 00:09:41,680
So don't worry about having enough food or drink or clothing.

116
00:09:42,180 --> 00:09:46,140
Why be like the pagans who are so deeply concerned about these things?

117
00:09:46,620 --> 00:09:50,320
Your heavenly Father already knows all your needs.

118
00:09:51,280 --> 00:09:54,700
And He will give you all you need from day to day

119
00:09:54,700 --> 00:10:00,580
if you live for Him and make the kingdom of God your primary concern.

120
00:10:02,300 --> 00:10:03,920
So don't worry about tomorrow.

121
00:10:04,880 --> 00:10:07,180
For tomorrow will bring its own worries.

122
00:10:08,100 --> 00:10:11,000
Today's trouble is enough for today.

123
00:10:13,660 --> 00:10:15,700
Let me share two points from this passage.

124
00:10:16,590 --> 00:10:19,830
One of my favorites on this whole issue of trust and giving.

125
00:10:20,410 --> 00:10:22,650
God, number one, wants us to do what?

126
00:10:22,950 --> 00:10:25,230
To trust in God's bank.

127
00:10:26,900 --> 00:10:29,920
Trust in the Lord's bank, if you will.

128
00:10:29,920 --> 00:10:33,980
Our banks, our stocks, our mutual funds here on earth,

129
00:10:34,320 --> 00:10:36,820
they produce a variety of rates of return.

130
00:10:36,960 --> 00:10:40,550
Some are going up, some are going down.

131
00:10:42,420 --> 00:10:44,560
And these investments are not always secure.

132
00:10:45,640 --> 00:10:48,480
But we need to invest for our futures, and that's true.

133
00:10:48,600 --> 00:10:50,520
And retirement investing is a good thing.

134
00:10:50,520 --> 00:10:55,700
But amassing a myriad of wealth just to have it is a foolish thing.

135
00:10:56,560 --> 00:11:01,420
Because one thing is certain, no matter how great or poorly your investments did on earth,

136
00:11:01,940 --> 00:11:05,480
you simply cannot take your fortunes with you.

137
00:11:07,080 --> 00:11:08,340
You cannot take them with you.

138
00:11:09,270 --> 00:11:10,470
It all stays here.

139
00:11:12,320 --> 00:11:15,840
You ever been to a junkyard or the dump?

140
00:11:17,800 --> 00:11:20,400
It all stays here, doesn't it?

141
00:11:21,460 --> 00:11:28,920
The latest and greatest stereo system that was out a few years ago is laying there in the pile.

142
00:11:29,700 --> 00:11:31,100
It all stays here.

143
00:11:31,800 --> 00:11:36,860
That beautiful car that you just saved for and dreamed about and looked forward to,

144
00:11:36,860 --> 00:11:43,810
eventually it sits in the junkyard full of rust and they smash it this tall.

145
00:11:45,060 --> 00:11:47,140
It's all going to stay here.

146
00:11:50,410 --> 00:11:52,070
We see those principles at work.

147
00:11:52,250 --> 00:11:53,650
Wealth doesn't ever satisfy.

148
00:11:53,770 --> 00:11:55,210
When you die, you leave it here.

149
00:11:55,970 --> 00:11:58,590
But friends, when you give to God's kingdom,

150
00:11:59,520 --> 00:12:01,140
when you give to God's kingdom,

151
00:12:01,140 --> 00:12:03,980
you get to see it used for His purposes,

152
00:12:04,380 --> 00:12:06,640
for His glory, for His outcomes,

153
00:12:07,180 --> 00:12:12,000
and it gets invested in the heavenly bank for your future.

154
00:12:13,760 --> 00:12:15,240
That's a better investment

155
00:12:15,240 --> 00:12:20,900
than what you can do right here in the bank down the street.

156
00:12:23,600 --> 00:12:26,940
As we saw last week, our possessions, our money, our stuff

157
00:12:26,940 --> 00:12:31,460
is to be used as a tool for ministry, for enlarging the kingdom of God

158
00:12:31,460 --> 00:12:36,280
and investing in your local church, investing in owning the vision

159
00:12:36,280 --> 00:12:40,480
has real returns as the kingdom of God grows here on earth

160
00:12:40,480 --> 00:12:41,900
through Fullerton First Baptist.

161
00:12:43,440 --> 00:12:47,670
And friends, I directly link the lives of these students

162
00:12:47,670 --> 00:12:53,250
that are being changed to your investing in your staff, in your facility,

163
00:12:53,430 --> 00:12:58,590
in praying for these people as they share Jesus in a place that is comfortable

164
00:12:58,590 --> 00:13:02,270
and ministers to our young people and to our medium-aged people

165
00:13:02,270 --> 00:13:04,950
and everybody in between and our old people and all of us.

166
00:13:05,350 --> 00:13:12,010
These lives being changed is because you've invested and prayed and asked God to move.

167
00:13:12,010 --> 00:13:17,740
and you can be proud of being a part of the kingdom of God

168
00:13:17,740 --> 00:13:22,540
as Jesus brings it here in this place and around the world.

169
00:13:25,360 --> 00:13:28,790
And all that money, all that money given,

170
00:13:30,320 --> 00:13:33,380
given to campaigns, given to the staff and the church here,

171
00:13:33,440 --> 00:13:37,840
and all that money given is also storing up treasures in heaven.

172
00:13:37,840 --> 00:13:42,680
It's investing in God's bank for an investment rate of return

173
00:13:42,680 --> 00:13:44,620
that is literally out of this world.

174
00:13:44,620 --> 00:13:51,300
and we can't take it when we leave.

175
00:13:52,820 --> 00:13:54,800
But the following was inscribed on a tombstone

176
00:13:54,800 --> 00:13:56,260
and I think it says volumes.

177
00:13:56,480 --> 00:13:59,220
It says, what I spent, I lost.

178
00:13:59,920 --> 00:14:02,840
What I saved, I left.

179
00:14:03,460 --> 00:14:05,880
But what I gave, I have.

180
00:14:07,390 --> 00:14:08,170
I like that.

181
00:14:09,510 --> 00:14:10,850
What I spent, I lost.

182
00:14:10,930 --> 00:14:12,210
What I saved, I left.

183
00:14:12,210 --> 00:14:16,670
But what I gave, I have in the kingdom forever.

184
00:14:17,680 --> 00:14:24,580
Friends, God wants us to trust in His heavenly bank, and two, He wants us to trust in His provision.

185
00:14:26,240 --> 00:14:35,700
We struggle, I think, to give to God, because deep down we're not sure that God is really going to come through and take care of us.

186
00:14:37,400 --> 00:14:45,600
It's one thing to talk about love and heaven and values and our souls and all of those topics here at church,

187
00:14:45,600 --> 00:14:49,020
but it's another thing to give our money

188
00:14:49,020 --> 00:14:51,500
and let God meet our needs in practical ways.

189
00:14:52,280 --> 00:14:53,860
It's one thing to come and hear

190
00:14:53,860 --> 00:14:56,360
of these kind of otherworldly concepts

191
00:14:56,360 --> 00:14:59,960
but to really trust that he's gonna meet your needs

192
00:14:59,960 --> 00:15:01,280
on a day-by-day basis,

193
00:15:01,640 --> 00:15:03,220
now that's down and dirty.

194
00:15:03,500 --> 00:15:07,270
That's hard because that's where we really live.

195
00:15:09,610 --> 00:15:10,790
And the question is this,

196
00:15:11,110 --> 00:15:14,400
do we really, really trust God?

197
00:15:15,640 --> 00:15:17,280
Do we really trust God?

198
00:15:19,730 --> 00:15:24,550
Matthew 6.33, but seek first His kingdom and His righteousness,

199
00:15:25,680 --> 00:15:28,560
and all these things will be given to you as well.

200
00:15:29,770 --> 00:15:33,290
He's saying all the things that you worry about in food and clothing and shelter,

201
00:15:33,290 --> 00:15:37,430
when you make the kingdom your first priority, God takes care of the rest.

202
00:15:41,510 --> 00:15:42,650
But do we believe it?

203
00:15:44,160 --> 00:15:45,660
Do we really believe this?

204
00:15:48,250 --> 00:15:49,890
Our giving records tell the story.

205
00:15:51,600 --> 00:15:55,780
As we've said, what we believe is accurately reflected in our checkbooks.

206
00:15:55,780 --> 00:16:02,260
What we really believe about God is reflected in how we live our lives and how we trust Him and how we give.

207
00:16:06,130 --> 00:16:12,830
When we're asked to follow God's design for our giving by giving our tithe of 10%, do we really believe this verse?

208
00:16:15,210 --> 00:16:21,410
When asked to follow God's challenge through owning the vision, do we really believe this verse?

209
00:16:23,720 --> 00:16:28,780
With regard to giving, you'll recall that God says to Malachi, test me in this.

210
00:16:30,140 --> 00:16:34,860
It's the only place I can find where God actually says, try me, test me.

211
00:16:38,990 --> 00:16:40,090
And I would say the same.

212
00:16:41,710 --> 00:16:43,450
Try God.

213
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:46,300
Try God.

214
00:16:46,580 --> 00:16:47,440
Try Him.

215
00:16:48,020 --> 00:16:51,460
Tell me the story when you trust Him and try God.

216
00:16:51,820 --> 00:16:54,020
Come and tell me how He met your needs.

217
00:16:54,160 --> 00:16:55,860
I love those testimonies.

218
00:16:57,120 --> 00:17:00,180
People sometimes pull me aside and say, it doesn't make sense, Pastor.

219
00:17:00,180 --> 00:17:02,700
This doesn't make sense, but I'm going to try it.

220
00:17:02,700 --> 00:17:04,220
I'm going to give my first fruits.

221
00:17:04,280 --> 00:17:05,600
And they come back a few weeks later.

222
00:17:05,740 --> 00:17:07,260
You won't believe what happened.

223
00:17:07,540 --> 00:17:08,560
And I just smile.

224
00:17:08,940 --> 00:17:09,880
I say, try me.

225
00:17:10,320 --> 00:17:12,780
And they share how God provided.

226
00:17:14,470 --> 00:17:18,910
And all I can do is share that and bang on the pulpit and say it over and over.

227
00:17:18,990 --> 00:17:22,390
But friends, you've got to try it to live it.

228
00:17:23,960 --> 00:17:25,740
And I'll just say it until I'm blue in the face.

229
00:17:25,940 --> 00:17:29,420
But you have to try it to really experience it.

230
00:17:29,540 --> 00:17:31,740
Jesus wants us to give.

231
00:17:31,860 --> 00:17:33,220
God says, test me in this.

232
00:17:35,210 --> 00:17:35,770
Try God.

233
00:17:38,650 --> 00:17:40,130
Try God as you tithe.

234
00:17:40,270 --> 00:17:42,670
Try God as you give above and beyond for this campaign

235
00:17:42,670 --> 00:17:44,830
and watch God take care of your needs.

236
00:17:45,410 --> 00:17:47,850
He might even bless you beyond what you can even imagine.

237
00:17:48,250 --> 00:17:48,910
Try Him.

238
00:17:49,550 --> 00:17:52,430
Trust in His provision, not just your own.

239
00:17:54,150 --> 00:17:54,610
Try Him.

240
00:17:56,430 --> 00:17:58,070
I want to close with this story,

241
00:17:58,470 --> 00:18:00,010
another set of tombstones.

242
00:18:00,980 --> 00:18:02,040
Seems to be a theme,

243
00:18:02,040 --> 00:18:04,780
but I think God is asking us to die to ourselves anyway

244
00:18:04,780 --> 00:18:05,480
in this area.

245
00:18:06,790 --> 00:18:10,140
Randy Alcorn, in this great book,

246
00:18:10,220 --> 00:18:11,020
The Treasure Principle,

247
00:18:11,020 --> 00:18:18,540
He shares this story about his trip to Cairo, Egypt, and some friends took the Alcorns down

248
00:18:18,540 --> 00:18:27,140
an alley in Cairo, and they entered this little graveyard for American missionaries in Cairo,

249
00:18:27,260 --> 00:18:27,520
Egypt.

250
00:18:29,020 --> 00:18:35,240
And as he describes, the grass was overgrown, and it was clearly a place that had been forgotten.

251
00:18:37,700 --> 00:18:44,540
And they were encouraged to turn their attention to a scorched tombstone there at their feet,

252
00:18:44,540 --> 00:18:52,380
And it read this, William Borden, 1887 to 1913.

253
00:18:55,440 --> 00:18:59,260
And they learned that William Borden was a graduate of Yale University.

254
00:19:00,280 --> 00:19:08,340
He was an heir to a great fortune, but he rejected that life of ease that easily could have been his.

255
00:19:09,000 --> 00:19:16,560
He rejected a life of living off the fortune in favor of bringing the good news of Jesus Christ to the Muslim world.

256
00:19:19,090 --> 00:19:24,510
In fact, he was so committed to that mission that he refused to even buy himself a car

257
00:19:24,510 --> 00:19:29,870
and instead gave away hundreds of thousands of dollars to missions.

258
00:19:31,700 --> 00:19:34,700
But after only four months of zealous ministry in Egypt,

259
00:19:34,700 --> 00:19:41,640
he contracted spinal meningitis and he died at the age of 25, a young man.

260
00:19:44,400 --> 00:19:51,260
The epitaph on that little sun-scorched tombstone there in the dusty, overgrown graveyard

261
00:19:51,260 --> 00:20:03,930
said this. It said, apart from faith in Christ, there is no explanation for such a life. Did you

262
00:20:03,930 --> 00:20:14,400
catch that? Apart from faith in Christ, there is no explanation for such a life. Shortly after they

263
00:20:14,400 --> 00:20:23,420
stared at that phrase on the tombstone, the Alcorns were then whisked away to the Egyptian

264
00:20:23,420 --> 00:20:32,770
Museum there in Cairo, the National Museum, and they took in another tombstone, if you will,

265
00:20:34,200 --> 00:20:43,520
and there they looked at the riches of King Tutankhamen, known as King Tut. King Tut died

266
00:20:43,520 --> 00:20:52,680
at a young age as well, at 17. He was buried with unimaginable riches, literally tons,

267
00:20:53,360 --> 00:20:54,720
Literally tons of gold.

268
00:20:55,980 --> 00:21:00,460
The Egyptians believed in the afterlife, where you could actually take your treasure with you.

269
00:21:01,160 --> 00:21:02,100
But here's the problem.

270
00:21:02,260 --> 00:21:08,700
Howard Carter found all those accoutrements from the grave, from the tomb,

271
00:21:09,480 --> 00:21:15,180
intact in one piece, sealed up in King Tut's tomb in 1922.

272
00:21:15,700 --> 00:21:19,980
They were never taken beyond that tomb.

273
00:21:21,590 --> 00:21:23,590
Untouched for more than 3,000 years.

274
00:21:26,150 --> 00:21:26,890
Two graves.

275
00:21:28,680 --> 00:21:30,260
One grave was obscure.

276
00:21:30,700 --> 00:21:32,100
One grave was dusty.

277
00:21:32,320 --> 00:21:36,660
One grave was hidden off the back alley of a street littered with garbage.

278
00:21:36,660 --> 00:21:40,680
The other grave was filled with wealth and opulence.

279
00:21:41,280 --> 00:21:43,320
But where are the two now?

280
00:21:44,920 --> 00:21:50,540
The one who lived in opulence exists in a Christless eternity.

281
00:21:51,540 --> 00:21:55,760
And the other who lived a modest life on earth, serving the true king,

282
00:21:55,760 --> 00:22:00,560
is enjoying his everlasting reward forever in the presence of Jesus.

283
00:22:03,290 --> 00:22:08,900
See, Tut's life was tragic because of an awful truth he discovered too late

284
00:22:08,900 --> 00:22:11,580
that you can't take your treasures with you.

285
00:22:12,720 --> 00:22:14,480
He couldn't take them on with him.

286
00:22:14,480 --> 00:22:17,620
The thousands of tons of gold and all that came with it,

287
00:22:17,780 --> 00:22:19,640
he couldn't take it with him.

288
00:22:21,600 --> 00:22:25,830
And William Borden's short life was triumphant

289
00:22:25,830 --> 00:22:29,650
because he sent his treasures on ahead.

290
00:22:31,580 --> 00:22:35,260
Tut hoarded, and it didn't do him any good.

291
00:22:37,090 --> 00:22:41,610
Borden gave it away, and he blessed so many people on earth,

292
00:22:42,890 --> 00:22:46,070
and now it's a blessing for him in heaven as well.

293
00:22:49,690 --> 00:22:54,460
What will you lay at Jesus' feet this Palm Sunday?

294
00:22:57,340 --> 00:23:00,340
Will you trust Jesus as your Lord and your Savior?

295
00:23:00,340 --> 00:23:03,160
Will you trust him to take care of your needs?

296
00:23:04,690 --> 00:23:08,770
And as I've said over and over, it's not necessarily all your wants.

297
00:23:09,230 --> 00:23:12,090
but he promises to take care of your needs.

298
00:23:13,970 --> 00:23:16,570
But I also know that when you trust him with your needs,

299
00:23:17,850 --> 00:23:19,090
that God is there to bless.

300
00:23:19,610 --> 00:23:22,050
You may not get all the things you want,

301
00:23:22,790 --> 00:23:26,920
but he'll enlarge your heart and make it soft

302
00:23:26,920 --> 00:23:29,720
and make it like his heart.

303
00:23:31,320 --> 00:23:35,380
That's a far better thing than just having more stuff.

304
00:23:37,140 --> 00:23:38,740
Will you trust him as the Lord and Savior

305
00:23:38,740 --> 00:23:39,680
to take care of your needs?

306
00:23:39,680 --> 00:23:41,940
And finally, when he asks you to invest

307
00:23:41,940 --> 00:23:43,540
that which is closest to your heart

308
00:23:43,540 --> 00:23:54,800
in His kingdom, will you trust Him? Will you trust Him? Will you obey our Father in heaven?

309
00:23:57,850 --> 00:24:08,660
You have set up a bank there that pays out unimaginable riches, but we are still convinced

310
00:24:08,660 --> 00:24:19,770
sometimes that Quaker Savings and Bank of America is still a better deal. Lord, help us to see an

311
00:24:19,770 --> 00:24:26,780
eternal perspective. Help us to see that You really are there in our lives and really do take

312
00:24:26,780 --> 00:24:35,670
care of us when we stretch and trust You and obey as You called us to. And so, Father, as we prepare

313
00:24:35,670 --> 00:24:42,450
to think about giving of our tithes and offerings and about stretching to pay off our debts here at

314
00:24:42,450 --> 00:24:47,030
our church, that we might liberate more monies down the road for ministry and not for debt

315
00:24:47,030 --> 00:24:55,560
retirement. Father, as we as a family struggle with what we are to give in that, I pray that

316
00:24:55,560 --> 00:25:03,230
these texts would become very real and that we'd really sit in our chair late at night

317
00:25:03,230 --> 00:25:13,330
and quietly just surrender to you, and then we'll trust and we'll obey. And I pray, Father,

318
00:25:13,430 --> 00:25:19,070
that for this congregation, that as they step out in faith, that you would richly bless and meet

319
00:25:19,070 --> 00:25:24,700
them there and take them to new places they couldn't even imagine because they've trusted

320
00:25:24,700 --> 00:25:32,260
and obeyed. So bless Fullerton first in this way, I pray, Father. May we really take these texts to

321
00:25:32,260 --> 00:25:41,900
heart, and may we meet you there at the crossroads, the place of our trust and our struggle. May you

322
00:25:41,900 --> 00:25:51,350
meet us, hold us, sustain us, and pour out your blessing. So, Father, we ask these things humbly,

323
00:25:52,860 --> 00:25:54,420
Looking forward to seeing what you will do.

324
00:25:55,490 --> 00:25:57,990
Continue, Father, to minister to us.

325
00:25:58,190 --> 00:25:59,910
May we minister to you in this holy week.

326
00:26:02,350 --> 00:26:04,650
And may it be a real encouragement for our souls.

327
00:26:07,080 --> 00:26:10,400
Good Friday, Saturday as you were in the ground,

328
00:26:11,550 --> 00:26:13,150
and Sunday when you rose again.

329
00:26:14,020 --> 00:26:17,520
Make that real to us, as real as the day it happened.

330
00:26:19,380 --> 00:26:22,480
And may that enlarge our faith and our trust in you.

331
00:26:23,990 --> 00:26:26,190
So we thank you for this time together as a family.

332
00:26:26,190 --> 00:26:30,880
May the rest of our day be a blessing, we pray in Jesus' name, and amen.

